Read Excel DATA and Convert to CSV¶
In [ ]:
import pandas as pd
years = [91,92,93,94,95,96,97,98,99,1400]
for year in years:
    addrs = './Datasets/Part1/veladat-'+str(year)+'.xlsx'
    xls = pd.ExcelFile(addrs)
    if len(xls.sheet_names) == 5:
        df = pd.read_excel(xls, xls.sheet_names[3])
        df.drop(df.head(3).index, inplace=True)
        df.rename(columns={df.columns[0]:'saal','Unnamed: 1': 'ostan','Unnamed: 2': '_sum','Unnamed: 3': 'man','Unnamed: 4': 'woman'}, inplace=True)
        df['saal'] = year
        addrs3 = './Datasets/Part1/modified/ByYear/veladat-'+str(year)+'.csv'
        df.to_csv(addrs3, index=False)    
    
    df1 = pd.DataFrame( columns=['saal','fasl','ostan','_sum','man','woman'])
    for fasl in xls.sheet_names[0:4]:
        df2 = pd.read_excel(xls, fasl)
        df2.drop(df2.head(3).index, inplace=True)
        df2.rename(columns={df2.columns[0]:'saal','Unnamed: 1': 'ostan','Unnamed: 2': '_sum','Unnamed: 3': 'man','Unnamed: 4': 'woman'}, inplace=True)
        df2['saal'] = year
        df2.insert(1,'fasl',fasl)
        df1 = pd.concat([df1,df2])  
    addrs2 = './Datasets/Part1/modified/BySeason/veladat-'+str(year)+'.csv'
    df1['saal'] = pd.to_numeric(df1['saal'])
    df1['_sum'] = pd.to_numeric(df1['_sum'])
    df1['man'] = pd.to_numeric(df1['man'])
    df1['woman'] = pd.to_numeric(df1['woman'])
    df1.to_csv(addrs2, index=False,header=False)

DROP TABLE IF EXISTS Iran_birth;

CREATE TABLE Iran_birth (
			saal INT,
			fasl VARCHAR(255),
            ostan VARCHAR(255),
            _sum INT,
            man INT,
	        woman INT
);

from bidi.algorithm import get_display
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import arabic_reshaper
from arabic_reshaper import reshape

def to_persian(tex):
    reshaped_text = arabic_reshaper.reshape(tex)
    bidi_text = get_display(reshaped_text)
    return bidi_text

x_96 = [get_display(reshape(x[0])) for x in birth_96]

def to_persian(tex):
    reshaped_text = arabic_reshaper.reshape(tex)
    bidi_text = get_display(reshaped_text)
    return bidi_text

def regularize_unicode(s):
    s=s.str.replace('','')
    s=s.str.replace('','')
    s=s.str.replace(chr(8204),'')
    return s

def make_df_of_rate(df_popu,birth ):
## df of birth of all men    
    df_birth = pd.DataFrame(birth,columns=['ostan','birth'])
    df_popu['ostan'] = regularize_unicode(df_popu['ostan'])
    df_birth['ostan'] = regularize_unicode(df_birth['ostan'])
    _df = pd.merge(df_birth, df_popu, on='ostan',how='outer')
    _df['nesbat'] = _df['birth']  /_df['Population'] 
    _df = _df.sort_values(by=['nesbat'],ascending=False).reset_index(drop = True)
    _df['ostan'] = [get_display(reshape(x)) for x in _df['ostan']]
    return _df

addrs = './Datasets/Part1/Iran_population.csv'
df_popu = pd.read_csv(addrs)
df_popu.set_axis(['ostan', 'Population'], axis=1, inplace=True)

Question 3 :¶

What are the disadvantages of cursors?

  • Uses more resources because Each time you fetch a row from the cursor, it results in a network roundtrip.
  • There are restrictions on the SELECT statements that can be used.
  • Because of the round trips, performance and speed is slow.

It is true that in some case we can avoid cursors by using PL SQL logics,I mean by implementing While loop,Tricky queries and through joins but they require great development logic.

If possible, avoid using SQL Server cursors. They generally use a lot of SQL Server resources and reduce the performance and scalability of your applications. If you need to perform row-by-row operations, try to find another method to perform the task.

Here are some alternatives to using a cursor:

  • Use WHILE LOOPS
  • Use temp tables
  • Use derived tables
